04288nam a22005055i 9780773564473DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735644737 a10.1515/97807735644732doi  a(DE-B1597)654992  a(OCoLC)1394872760  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJL27.5bW47 1994eb 7aPOL0400002bisacsh04a342.71/031 aWebber, Jeremy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReimagining Canada :bLanguage, Culture, Community, and the Canadian Constitution /cJeremy Webber. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tCrisis and Community -- tNational Identity and Constitutional Change, 1960 to 1992 -- tIntroduction to Part One -- tCompeting Nationalisms, Competing Identities -- tConstitutional Themes -- tTowards Patriation: Constitutional Reform, 1960—1982 -- tAfter Patriation: Aboriginal Rights, Meech Lake, and Charlottetown, 1982-1992 -- tConclusion to Part One -- tPolitical Allegiance, Political Community, and the Canadian Constitution -- tLanguage, Culture, and Political Community -- tAn Asymmetrical Constitution -- tPractical Implications -- tConclusion -- tThe Canadian Conversation -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWebber begins by showing how different conceptions of culture, language, and nation shaped Canada's constitutional negotiations from 1960 until the referendum of 1992. He then calls for a reconception of the terms of the debate, claiming that the terms now used, often borrowed from quite different societies, have made resolution of the constitutional issues more difficult. He rejects the language of nation and nationalism, and the tendency towards exclusiveness implicit in that language, arguing for a Canadian community founded not on a rigid set of "shared values" but on shared debates and shared engagements through time. Recognizing that Canadians belong simultaneously to the larger community and to other more local communities each generating its own sense of allegiance Webber describes how their relationships are shaped by institutional, linguistic, and cultural factors and notes that these multiple influences produce an asymmetrical structure. He maintains that this structure should be reflected in an assymetrical constitution, and can be accommodated without undermining individual rights. Webber offers both an overview of the constitutional negotiations and a set of reflections on the appropriate relationship between culture, language, and political community in Canada. These reflections, while rooted in the Canadian context, hold lessons for other pluralistic federations, or for nations confronting similar issues of cultural accommodation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356447340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564473423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564473/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles